âš–ï¸ Core Message
A motion to reconsider is not a second bite. Use it to correct clear error, address new law or new evidence, or prevent manifest injustice â€” not to reâ€‘argue what was already decided. Pick the right rule and be precise.

ğŸ“– Lesson Content
â€¢ Which Rule? ğŸ§­ â€” Use Rule 59(e) to alter or amend a **final judgment** (within 28 days). Use Rule 54(b) (and any local rule) to reconsider **interlocutory** orders before final judgment.
â€¢ Proper Grounds ğŸ¯ â€” (1) Clear error of law or fact; (2) Newly discovered evidence (despite diligence); (3) Intervening change in controlling law; (4) To prevent manifest injustice.
â€¢ What Itâ€™s Not ğŸš« â€” Not for arguments or evidence that could have been raised before; not a chance to expand the brief. Keep it tight and targeted.
â€¢ Appellate Clock â±ï¸ â€” A timely Rule 59(e) motion tolls the time to appeal. Interlocutory reconsideration typically does not. Know your deadlines.
â€¢ Format & Proof ğŸ“‘ â€” Attach the new authority/evidence, explain diligence, and propose a corrected order. Observe local page limits and certification requirements.
ğŸ“ Assignment
Draft a **Motion to Reconsider** that:
1) Identifies whether Rule 59(e) (final) or Rule 54(b)/local rule (interlocutory) applies;
2) States one proper ground (clear error, new evidence, or intervening law) with pinâ€‘cites;
3) Explains diligence (for new evidence) or the precise legal error;
4) Attaches the evidence/authority; and
5) Includes a short Proposed Order.

